{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17596867","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17596867"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:18:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:18:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15413"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15413","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15413"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0,0,0.07,0.93,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8104"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69334"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8104","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8104"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15413"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54787"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"8761"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19656"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19659"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"69334","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/69334"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe liver contains specialised blood vessels that are crucial for its function. These vessels have unique structural features including a fenestrated endothelium and absence of a basement membrane.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary function of hepatic sinusoids?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Formation of plasma proteins","Storage of vitamin B12","Production of bile acids","Exchange between portal blood and hepatocytes","Synthesis of clotting factors"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe hepatic sinusoids are specialised capillary channels within the liver that have unique structural and functional characteristics. \u003Cstrong\u003EExchange between portal blood and hepatocytes\u003C/strong\u003E is their primary function, facilitated by their distinctive anatomy. The sinusoids have a fenestrated endothelium and lack a traditional basement membrane, allowing for efficient bidirectional transfer of substances between the blood and hepatocytes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFormation of plasma proteins\u003C/strong\u003E is a function of hepatocytes rather than sinusoids. While sinusoids deliver amino acids to hepatocytes and allow export of synthesised proteins, they do not directly synthesise these proteins.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStorage of vitamin B12\u003C/strong\u003E occurs within hepatocytes after transport across the sinusoidal membrane, but is not a function of the sinusoids themselves.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProduction of bile acids\u003C/strong\u003E is performed by hepatocytes, not sinusoids. Bile acids are synthesised from cholesterol within hepatocytes and secreted into bile canaliculi.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESynthesis of clotting factors\u003C/strong\u003E is another function of hepatocytes, not sinusoids, though sinusoids deliver necessary components for this process.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe space between the sinusoidal endothelium and hepatocytes, known as the Space of Disse, is particularly important as it allows direct contact between blood plasma and the microvilli of hepatocytes. This arrangement facilitates the liver\u0027s crucial roles in protein synthesis, detoxification, and various metabolic functions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Hepatic sinusoids are specialised capillary beds with fenestrated endothelium and no basement membrane.","The primary function of hepatic sinusoids is to facilitate exchange between portal blood and hepatocytes.","The Space of Disse between sinusoids and hepatocytes enables efficient metabolic exchange and protein synthesis."],"references":["Brunt EM, Gouw AS, Hubscher SG, Tiniakos DG, Bedossa P, Burt AD, Callea F, Clouston AD, Dienes HP, Goodman ZD, Roberts EA, Roskams T, Terracciano L, Torbenson MS, Wanless IR. Pathology of the liver sinusoids. Histopathology. 2014 Jun;64(7):907-20. doi: 10.1111/his.12364. Epub 2014 Mar 8. PMID: 24393125.","Gibert-Ramos A, Sanfeliu-Redondo D, Aristu-Zabalza P, Mart\u00ednez-Alcocer A, Gracia-Sancho J, Guix\u00e9-Muntet S, Fern\u00e1ndez-Iglesias A. The Hepatic Sinusoid in Chronic Liver Disease: The Optimal Milieu for Cancer. Cancers (Basel). 2021 Nov 15;13(22):5719. doi: 10.3390/cancers13225719. PMID: 34830874; PMCID: PMC8616349.","Nightingale, J. M. (2012). Applied anatomy and physiology of the gastrointestinal tract (GIT). Gastrointestinal Tract Imaging E-Book: Gastrointestinal Tract Imaging E-Book, 45.","Podolsky, D. K., Camilleri, M., Fitz, J. G., Kalloo, A. N., Shanahan, F., \u0026 Wang, T. C. (Eds.). (2015). Yamada\u0027s textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons.","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54787"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15413"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"54787","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/54787"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-11T19:52:22+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-11T19:55:29+10:30"},"